    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. To answer your question, when you're sprinting at high intensity, your muscles undergo a rapid shift from aerobic to anaerobic metabolism. This means that the mitochondria, which are the energy-producing structures within muscle cells, are not able to keep up with the demand for energy.\n\nAs a result, the muscle cells start to break down glucose and convert it into lactic acid through anaerobic glycolysis. This process is highly inefficient and produces a significant amount of lactic acid, which accumulates in the muscle cells.\n\nThe buildup of lactic acid leads to a decrease in the pH levels within the muscle cells, causing the pH to drop. This decrease in pH triggers the activation of various ion channels and receptors on the surface of the muscle fibers, which leads to the release of neurotransmitters such as substance P and calcitonin gene-related peptide (CGRP).\n\nThese neurotransmitters bind to receptors on the nerve endings, which triggers the sensation of pain and burning. The pain is thought to be mediated by the activation of nociceptors, which are specialized nerve endings that detect changes in pH and other chemical signals.\n\nIn terms of the pH levels, when the pH drops",
      "source": "target",
